BRUCELLA MELITENSIS - NETHERLANDS: MYCOBACTERIAL CULTURE CONTAMINATION
**********************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 22 Jun 2012
Source: Omroep Gelderland (Broadcasting Gelderland) [in Dutch, machine trans., edited]
http://www.omroepgelderland.nl/web/Nieuws-1/1608451/Tbcmonsters-besmet-met-bacterie.htm


On 21 May 2012, tuberculosis samples sent from a laboratory in Nijmegen to laboratories in the rest of the Netherlands have been found to be contaminated by the bacterium _Brucella melitensis_. It causes brucellosis, also called Malta fever. Symptoms may include fever, headache, fatigue, malaise, and sweating.

The Nijmegen research laboratory has asked that all laboratories submit a list of employees who have worked with the samples and observe them for the development of any symptoms.

Unrecognized, brucellosis can become chronic and in some cases, serious complications such as heart valve infection and central nervous system infection may occur. The disease can be treated with antimicrobial agents.

--
