[Although not specifically stated so, it may be the case that the specimens were forwarded to other laboratories in the Netherlands to assess the ability of the labs to isolate and identify the pathogen. These specimens are now reported to be contaminated with _Brucella melitensis_, one of the species of brucellae that cause infections in humans. Concern regarding the spread of brucellae in the clinical laboratory is real, for example references 1-3, and specimens with the possibility of brucellae in culture should be handled in an appropriate isolation to prevent aerosol spread, which can occur with high attack rates in the lab, related to the ability of a low inoculum to cause infection. Post-exposure prophylaxis is often recommended, often with the combination of doxycycline and rifampin for 21 days.

References
----------
1. Martin-Mazuelos E, Nogales MC, Florez C, et al: Outbreak of _Brucella melitensis_ among microbiology laboratory workers. J Clin Microbiol. 1994; 32(8): 2035-6; available at http://jcm.asm.org/content/32/8/2035.
2. Fiori PL, Mastroandrea S, Rappelli P, Cappuccinelli P: _Brucella abortus_ infection acquired in microbiology laboratories. J Clin Microbiol. 2000; 38(5): 2005-6; available at http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC86653.
3. Yagupsky P, Baron EJ: Laboratory exposures to brucellae and implications for bioterrorism. Emerg Infect Dis 2005; 11(8): 1180-5; available at http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3320509. - Mod.LL

